I actually think very little of the game is stock shenanigans. I think the core of the game is M&A. Regarding stock, what the game does differently from other titles is it punishes you for having an overpriced company (like the real stock market).
Is that different from ipo games when you have shares at ipo where you can sell them after buying?
I thought you didn't like that mechanic. Maybe it's just me whom despise that

Yes, I think its different. In IPO games, you buy then sell when the IPO is below the market price, which has little to do with how good of a company it is. In 1817, you short when the future payouts of a company is small in comparison to what a share price is worth...essentially a cheap loan.
I really like when a game links share price and actual performance of the company as it brings gameplay to both aspects.
Willing to participate in shorting but not alone
